<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">What Is Sourdough Starter?</h3>



<p class=3D"p1">A sourdough starter is a live, fermented culture of flour a=
nd water filled with wild yeast and bacteria from our environment. A small =
portion is added to sourdough bread dough to make it rise. <strong>Commerci=
al yeast IS NOT required.</strong></p>



<p>Sounds a bit weird, right? Of course it does. Know this: natural =E2=80=
=9Cwild=E2=80=9D yeast is all around us. It can be found in a bag of flour,=
 in the air, on your hands etc. Just because you can=E2=80=99t see it, does=
n=E2=80=99t mean it=E2=80=99s not there and doing its thing. <em>It=E2=80=
=99s like magic.</em></p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How Long Will It Take?</h3>



<p>To create a sourdough starter from scratch, the overall process will tak=
e 7 days (or more) from start to finish. <strong>It=E2=80=99s not instant.<=
/strong> First, you=E2=80=99ll create the starter with <a href=3D"https://a=
mzn.to/2tX1FMl" rel=3D"nofollow">whole wheat flour</a> to jumpstart ferment=
ation. Then, you=E2=80=99ll continue to feed it with regular <a href=3D"htt=
p://amazon.com/gp/product/B00P6EQGW6/ref=3Das_li_tl?ie=3DUTF8&amp;tag=3Demi=
lieraffa-20&amp;camp=3D1789&amp;creative=3D9325&amp;linkCode=3Das2&amp;crea=
tiveASIN=3DB00P6EQGW6&amp;linkId=3D91dcd4032aacffafbb966072073757e2" rel=3D=
"nofollow">all purpose flour</a> or bread flour to cultivate the wild yeast=
s and friendly bacteria. Once it=E2=80=99s created, you=E2=80=99ll keep it =
alive with ongoing feedings and care, which you can read about <a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.theclevercarrot.com/2021/01/feeding-sourdough-starter-my-best-ti=
ps-tricks">here.</a></p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">When Will It Be Ready To Use?</h3>



<p><strong>Your starter is ready to use when it has doubled in size, with p=
lenty of bubbles on the surface and throughout the culture.</strong></p>



<p class=3D"has-quaternary-background-color has-background"><strong>NOTE:</=
strong> It=E2=80=99s not uncommon for it to take <strong>up to two weeks</s=
trong> or more for the starter to become active. It all depends. I know thi=
s timeframe sounds a bit vague, but growing yeast in a jar (that=E2=80=99s =
basically what you=E2=80=99re doing) can be unpredictable at times. Please =
be patient if the process takes time for you- it=E2=80=99s normal.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Is It Difficult To Do?</h3>



<p class=3D"p1">Absolutely not! In short: you=E2=80=99re basically adding f=
lour and water to a jar, feeding it with <em>more</em> flour and water and =
waiting for it to become bubbly, active and double in size. That=E2=80=99s =
it. Most of your time involvement is hands-off. Can I ask you a favor thoug=
h? <strong>Don=E2=80=99t overthink it.</strong> There=E2=80=99s a ton of so=
urdough information out there, and you <em>will</em> fall down a major rabb=
it hole if you start poking around. Just stick to this tutorial for now, fo=
llow the steps as written and just go for it.</p>



