			<h3 data-tasty-recipes-customization=3D"h3-color.color h3-transform.text=
-transform">Description</h3>
			<div class=3D"tasty-recipes-description-body" data-tasty-recipes-customi=
zation=3D"body-color.color">
				<p>Looking for an easy, sourdough starter recipe for beginners? Adapted=
 from my bestselling book <a href=3D"https://amzn.to/2ToAvZQ" target=3D"_bl=
ank" rel=3D"nofollow noopener"><em>Artisan Sourdough Made Simple,&nbsp;</em=
></a>follow my no-nonsense, step-by-step guide for practical tips, tricks, =
and ongoing care- anyone can do it. Use it to make my famous golden, crusty=
 <a href=3D"https://www.theclevercarrot.com/2014/01/sourdough-bread-a-begin=
ners-guide">sourdough bread recipe.</a></p>
<p><strong><em>Please read my notes below before you begin.</em></strong></=
p>
<h4>Notes, Tips &amp; Expectations:</h4>
<ul>
<li>Download &amp; print personal sourdough starter feeding chart <a href=
=3D"https://theclevercarrot.myflodesk.com/newsletter">{here}</a>.&nbsp;</li=
>
<li>The overall process takes ~7+ days, <em><strong>if the temperature is</=
strong> <strong>warm enough, ideally 70-75 F.</strong> </em>However, it can=
 take up to 2+ weeks or more for a strong starter to become established. Do=
 not ignore the importance of temperature.</li>
<li>Growth will <em>seem</em> to <strong>slow down on Days 3-4.</strong> Th=
is delay is commonly called a =E2=80=9Cfalse=E2=80=9D start. It=E2=80=99s a=
lso normal- the yeast needs time to cultivate. Please be patient!</li>
<li>You will need one large 3/4 L jar, or something of similar size (I use =
<a href=3D"https://amzn.to/2Sd5wCJ" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"nofollow noope=
ner">this one</a>). Place a rubber band or piece of masking tape around the=
 jar to measure the starter=E2=80=99s growth as it rises.</li>
<li>To clarify feeding your starter: <strong>=E2=80=9Cequal parts=E2=80=9D<=
/strong> refers to <strong>equal weights only</strong>, not measuring cups.=
 Example: <strong>60 g</strong> (1/2 cup) flour + <strong>60 g</strong> (1/=
4 cup) water. Same weight. <em>Different volume</em>. Not a typo. Why? Flou=
r is light, fluffy and full of air pockets, so it takes up more space in a =
measuring cup (but weighs less than water). Water is more dense and compact=
; it takes up less space but weighs more than flour. <em><strong>That=E2=80=
=99s why their cup measurements don=E2=80=99t match, even when their weight=
s are identical.</strong></em> Many bakers get confused by this. I=E2=80=99=
ve included volume measurements for convenience since not everyone owns a s=
cale. But, do choose one measurement system and stick with it for feeding!<=
/li>
</ul>
			</div>
		</div>
